properties.name: Tycho
properties.description: One of the most prominent craters, with a ray system extending over 1,500 km. Named after astronomer Tycho Brahe. Relatively young at 108 million years old.

properties.name: Copernicus
properties.description: Called the 'Monarch of the Moon' by early observers. Prominent ray system, terraced walls, and complex central peaks. Defines the 'Copernican' geological period.

properties.name: Aristarchus
properties.description: The brightest feature on the lunar surface. So bright it can be seen with the naked eye. Located on the Aristarchus Plateau with numerous volcanic features.

properties.name: Kepler
properties.description: Young, bright ray crater in Oceanus Procellarum. Named after Johannes Kepler. Ray system overlaps with Copernicus rays.

properties.name: Plato
properties.description: Large, dark-floored crater on the northern shore of Mare Imbrium. The floor was flooded with lava, making it unusually flat and dark.
properties.age: Ancient, but lava-flooded ~3.8 billion years ago

properties.name: Clavius
properties.description: One of the largest craters visible from Earth. Contains a distinctive arc of smaller craters on its floor, decreasing in size.

properties.name: Ptolemaeus
properties.description: Large ancient crater near the center of the near side. Part of a prominent chain with Alphonsus and Arzachel. Floor is remarkably flat, filled with lava.

properties.name: Alphonsus
properties.description: Site of possible transient lunar phenomena (outgassing). Ranger 9 crash-landed here in 1965, sending back live TV footage.

properties.name: Archimedes
properties.description: Large, flooded crater in Mare Imbrium. The lava that filled the mare also flooded this crater, giving it an unusually smooth floor.

properties.name: Eratosthenes
properties.description: Located at the end of the Apennine Mountains. Defines the 'Eratosthenian' geological period (between 3.2 and 1.1 billion years ago). No ray system.

properties.name: Theophilus
properties.description: Impressive crater with a large central peak (1400m high) and terraced walls. Overlaps the older crater Cyrillus, demonstrating its younger age.

properties.name: Gassendi
properties.description: Located on the north rim of Mare Humorum. Floor contains a complex system of rilles and a central peak group. Site of reported transient phenomena.

properties.name: Schickard
properties.description: One of the largest craters on the near side. Floor has distinctive light and dark patches â€“ partially flooded with lava.

properties.name: Grimaldi
properties.description: Near the western limb. One of the darkest features on the Moon. Floor is very dark, flooded with basalt.

properties.name: Langrenus
properties.description: Large crater near the eastern limb. Has terraced walls and a complex central peak. Bright ray system visible at high sun angles.
